1 BE I T ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
2 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
3 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.1 of Title 63, unless there
4 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
5 This act shall be known and may be cited as the “Uniform Health
6 Care Decisions Act of 2026”.
7 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.2 of Title 63, unless there
9 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 As used in this act:
11 1. “Advance health care directive” means a power of attorney
12 for health care, health care instruction, or both. The term
13 includes an advance mental health care directive;
14 2. “Advance mental health care directive” means a power of
15 attorney for health care, health care instruction, or both, created
16 under Section 9 of this act;
17 3. “Agent” means an individual appointed under a power of
18 attorney for health care to make a health care decision for the
19 individual who made the appointment. The term includes a coagent or
20 alternate agent appointed under Section 20 of this act;
21 4. “Capacity” means having capacity under Section 3 of this
22 act;
23 5. “Cohabitant” means each of two individuals who have been
24 living together as a couple for at least one (1) year after each
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 3

1 beca me an adult or was emancipated and who are not married to one
2 another;
3 6. “Default surrogate” means an individual authorized under
4 Section 12 of this act to make a health care decision for another
5 individual;
6 7. “Electronic” means relating to technology having electrical,
7 digital, magnetic, wireless, optical, electromagnetic, or similar
8 capabilities;
9 8. “Family member” means a spouse, domestic partner, adult
10 child, parent, or grandparent, or an adult descendant of a spouse,
11 child, parent, or grandparent;
12 9. “Guardian” means a person appointed under law by a court to
13 make decisions regarding the personal affairs of an individual,
14 which may include health care decisions. The term does not include
15 a guardian ad litem;
16 10. “Health care” means care or treatment or a service or
17 procedure to maintain, monitor, diagnose, or otherwise affect an
18 individual’s physical or mental illness, injury, or condition. The
19 term includes mental health care;
20 11. “Health care decision” means a decision made by an
21 individual or the individual’s surrogate regarding the individual’s
22 health care, including:
23 a. selection or discharge of a health care professional
24 or health care institution,
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 4

1 b. approval or disapproval of a diagnostic test, surgical
2 procedure, medication, therapeutic intervention, or
3 other health care,
4 c. direction to provide, withhold, or withdraw mechanical
5 ventilation or other health care, and
6 d. direction to provide, withhold, or withdraw
7 artificially administered hydration or nutrition,
8 subject to the limitations of the Hydration and
9 Nutrition for Incompetent Patients Act;
10 12. “Health care institution” means a facility or agency
11 licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized or permitted by other
12 law to provide health care in this state in the ordinary course of
13 business;
14 13. “Health care instruction” means a direction, whether or not
15 in a record, made by an individual that indicates the individual’s
16 goals, preferences, or wishes concerning the provision, withholding,
17 or withdrawal of health care. The term includes a direction
18 intended to be effective if a specified condition arises;
19 14. “Health care professional” means a physician or other
20 individual licensed, certified, or otherwise authorized or permitted
21 by other law of this state to provide health care in this state in
22 the ordinary course of business or the practice of the physician’s
23 or individual’s profession;
24 15. “Individual” means an adult or emancipated minor;
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 5

1 16. “Life-sustaining care” and “life-sustaining treatment” mean
2 health care that, in reasonable medical judgment, will be most
3 likely to be effective in ameliorating an individual’s life-
4 threatening conditions;
5 17. “Mental health care” means care or treatment or a service
6 or procedure to maintain, monitor, diagnose, or otherwise affect an
7 individual’s mental illness or other psychiatric, psychological, or
8 psychosocial condition;
9 18. “Nursing home” means a nursing facility as defined in
10 Section 1919(a)(1) of the Social Security Act, 42 U.S.C., Section
11 1396r(a)(1), as amended, or skilled nursing facility as defined in
12 Section 1819(a)(1) of the Social Security Act, 42 U.S.C., Section
13 1395i–3(a)(1), as amended;
14 19. “Person” means an individual, estate, business or nonprofit
15 entity, government or governmental subdivision, agency, or
16 instrumentality, or other legal entity;
17 20. “Person interested in the welfare of the individual” means:
18 a. the individual’s surrogate,
19 b. a family member of the individual,
20 c. the cohabitant of the individual,
21 d. a public entity providing health care case management
22 or protective services to the individual,
23
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 6

1 e. a person appointed under other law to make decisions
2 for the individual under a power of attorney for
3 finances, or
4 f. a person that has an ongoing personal or professional
5 relationship with the individual, including a person
6 that has provided educational or health care services
7 or supported decision making to the individual;
8 21. “Physician” means an individual authorized to practice
9 medicine from the State Board of Medical Licensure and Supervision
10 or the State Board of Osteopathic Examiners;
11 22. “Power of attorney for health care” means a record in which
12 an individual appoints an agent to make health care decisions for
13 the individual;
14 23. “Reasonable medical judgment” means a health care judgment
15 that would be made by a reasonably prudent physician knowledgeable
16 about the medical conditions involved and the treatment
17 possibilities with respect to such conditions;
18 24. “Reasonably available” means being able to be contacted
19 without undue effort and being willing and able to act in a timely
20 manner considering the urgency of an individual’s health care
21 situation. When used to refer to an agent or default surrogate, the
22 term includes being willing and able to comply with the duties under
23 Section 17 of this act in a timely manner considering the urgency of
24 an individual’s health care situation;
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 7

1 25. “Record” means information:
2 a. inscribed on a tangible medium, or
3 b. stored in an electronic or other medium and
4 retrievable in perceivable form;
5 26. “Responsible health care professional” means:
6 a. a health care professional designated by an individual
7 or the individual’s surrogate to have primary
8 responsibility for the individual’s health care or for
9 overseeing a course of treatment, or
10 b. in the absence of a designation under subparagraph a
11 of this paragraph, or if the professional designated
12 under subparagraph a of this paragraph is not
13 reasonably available, a health care professional who
14 has primary responsibility for overseeing the
15 individual’s health care or for overseeing a course of
16 treatment;
17 27. “Sign” means with present intent to authenticate or adopt a
18 record:
19 a. executing or adopting a tangible symbol, or
20 b. attaching to or logically associating with the record
21 an electronic symbol, sound, or process;
22 28. “State” means a state of the United States, the District of
23 Columbia, the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, the United States Virgin
24 Islands, or any other territory, or possession subject to the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 8

1 juri sdiction of the United States. The term includes a federally
2 recognized Indian tribe;
3 29. “Supported decision making” means assistance, from one or
4 more persons of an individual’s choosing, that helps the individual
5 make or communicate a decision, including by helping the individual
6 understand the nature and consequences of the decision; and
7 30. “Surrogate” means:
8 a. an agent,
9 b. a default surrogate, or
10 c. a guardian authorized to make health care decisions.
11 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
12 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.3 of Title 63, unless there
13 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
14 A. An individual has capacity for the purpose of this act if
15 the individual:
16 1. Is willing and able to communicate a decision independently
17 or with appropriate services, technological assistance, supported
18 decision making, or other reasonable accommodation; and
19 2. In making or revoking:
20 a. a health care decision, understands the nature and
21 consequences of the decision, including the primary
22 risks and benefits of the decision,
23 b. a health care instruction, understands the nature and
24 consequences of the instruction, including the primary
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 9

1 risks and benefits of the choices expressed in the
2 instruction, and
3 c. an appointment of an agent under a health care power
4 of attorney or identification of a default surrogate
5 under paragraph 1 of subsection B of Section 12 of
6 this act, recognizes the identity of the individual
7 being appointed or identified and understands the
8 general nature of the relationship of the individual
9 making the appointment or identification with the
10 individual being appointed or identified.
11 B. The right of an individual who has capacity to make a
12 decision about the individual’s health care is not affected by
13 whether the individual creates or revokes an advance health care
14 directive.
15 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.4 of Title 63, unless there
17 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 A. An individual is presumed to have capacity to make or revoke
19 a health care decision, health care instruction, and power of
20 attorney for health care unless:
21 1. A court has found the individual lacks capacity to do so; or
22 2. The presumption is rebutted under subsection B of this
23 section.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 10

1 B. Subject to Sections 5 and 6 of this act, a presumption under
2 subsection A of this section may be rebutted by a finding that the
3 individual lacks capacity:
4 1. Subject to subsection C of this section, made on the basis
5 of a contemporaneous examination by any of the following:
6 a. a physician,
7 b. a psychologist licensed or otherwise authorized to
8 practice in this state,
9 c. an individual with training and expertise in the
10 finding of lack of capacity who is licensed or
11 otherwise authorized to practice in this state as an
12 Advanced Practice Registered Nurse, a physician
13 assistant, or a social worker, or
14 d. a responsible health care professional not described
15 in subparagraph a, b, or c of this paragraph if:
16 (1) the individual about whom the finding is to be
17 made is experiencing a health condition requiring
18 a decision regarding health care treatment to be
19 made promptly to avoid loss of life or serious
20 harm to the health of the individual, and
21 (2) an individual listed in subparagraph a, b, or c
22 of this paragraph is not reasonably available;
23
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 11

1 2. Made in accordance with accepted standards of the profession
2 and the scope of practice of the individual making the finding and
3 to a reasonable degree of certainty; and
4 3. Documented in a record signed by the individual making the
5 finding that includes an opinion of the cause, nature, extent, and
6 probable duration of the lack of capacity.
7 C. The finding under subsection B of this section may not be
8 made by:
9 1. A family member of the individual presumed to have capacity;
10 2. The cohabitant of the individual or a descendant of the
11 cohabitant; or
12 3. The individual’s surrogate, a family member of the
13 surrogate, or a descendant of the surrogate.
14 D. If the finding under subsection B of this section was based
15 on a condition the individual no longer has or a responsible health
16 care professional subsequently has good cause to believe the
17 individual has capacity, the individual is presumed to have capacity
18 unless a court finds the individual lacks capacity or the
19 presumption is rebutted under subsection B of this section.
20 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.5 of Title 63, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. As soon as reasonably feasible, an individual who makes a
24 finding under subsection B of Section 4 of this act shall inform the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 12

1 indi vidual about whom the finding was made or the individual’s
2 responsible health care professional of the finding.
3 B. As soon as reasonably feasible, a responsible health care
4 professional who is informed of a finding under subsection B of
5 Section 4 of this act shall inform the individual about whom the
6 finding was made and the individual’s surrogate.
7 C. An individual found under subsection B of Section 4 of this
8 act to lack capacity may object to the finding:
9 1. By orally informing a responsible health care professional;
10 2. In a record provided to a responsible health care
11 professional or the health care institution in which the individual
12 resides or is receiving care; or
13 3. By another act that clearly indicates the individual’s
14 objection.
15 D. If the individual objects under subsection C of this
16 section, the finding under subsection B of Section 4 of this act is
17 not sufficient to rebut a presumption of capacity under subsection A
18 of Section 4 of this act and the individual shall be treated as
19 having capacity unless:
20 1. The individual withdraws the objection;
21 2. A court finds the individual lacks the presumed capacity;
22 3. The individual is experiencing a health condition requiring
23 a decision regarding health care treatment to be made promptly to
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 13

1 avoi d imminent loss of life or serious harm to the health of the
2 individual; or
3 4. Subject to subsection B of this section, the finding is
4 confirmed by a second finding made by an individual authorized under
5 paragraph 1 of subsection B of Section 4 of this act who:
6 a. did not make the first finding,
7 b. is not a family member of the individual who made the
8 first finding, and
9 c. is not the cohabitant of the individual who made the
10 first finding or a descendant of the cohabitant.
11 E. Neither a finding in the circumstances described in
12 paragraph 3 of subsection D of this section nor a second finding
13 that the individual lacks capacity under paragraph 4 of subsection D
14 of this section shall be sufficient to rebut the presumption of
15 capacity if the individual is requesting the provision or
16 continuation of life-sustaining treatment and the finding is being
17 used to make a decision to withhold or withdraw the treatment.
18 F. As soon as reasonably feasible, a health care professional
19 who is informed of an objection under subsection C of this section
20 shall:
21 1. Communicate the objection to a responsible health care
22 professional; and
23 2. Document the objection and the date of the objection in the
24 individual’s medical record or communicate the objection and the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 14

1 date of the objection to an administrator with responsibility for
2 medical records of the health care institution providing health care
3 to the individual, who shall document the objection and the date of
4 the objection in the individual’s medical record.
5 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
6 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.6 of Title 63, unless there
7 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
8 A. An individual found under subsection B of Section 4 of this
9 act to lack capacity, a responsible health care professional, the
10 health care institution providing health care to the individual, or
11 a person interested in the welfare of the individual may petition
12 the court in the respective county in which the individual resides
13 or is located to determine whether the individual lacks capacity.
14 B. The court in which a petition under subsection A of this
15 section is filed shall appoint legal counsel to represent the
16 individual if the individual does not have legal counsel. The court
17 shall hear the petition as soon as possible, but not later than
18 seven (7) days after the petition is filed. As soon as possible,
19 but not later than seven (7) days after the hearing, the court shall
20 determine whether the individual lacks capacity. The court may
21 determine that the individual lacks capacity only if the court finds
22 by clear and convincing evidence that the individual lacks capacity.
23
