1 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.7 of Title 63, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. An individual may create a health care instruction that
5 expresses the individual’s preferences for future health care,
6 including preferences regarding:
7 1. Health care professionals or health care institutions;
8 2. How a health care decision will be made and communicated;
9 3. Persons that should or should not be consulted regarding a
10 health care decision;
11 4. A person to serve as guardian for the individual if one is
12 appointed; and
13 5. An individual to serve as a default surrogate.
14 B. A health care professional to whom an individual
15 communicates or provides an instruction under subsection A of this
16 section shall document the instruction and the date of the
17 instruction in the individual’s medical record or communicate the
18 instruction and date of the instruction to an administrator with
19 responsibility for medical records of the health care institution
20 providing health care to the individual, who shall document the
21 instruction and the date of the instruction in the individual’s
22 medical record.
23 C. A health care instruction made by an individual that
24 conflicts with an earlier health care instruction made by the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 16

1 indi vidual, including an instruction documented in a medical order,
2 revokes the earlier instruction to the extent of the conflict.
3 D. A health care instruction may be in the same record as a
4 power of attorney for health care.
5 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
6 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.8 of Title 63, unless there
7 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
8 A. An individual may create a power of attorney for health care
9 to appoint an agent to make health care decisions for the
10 individual.
11 B. An individual shall be disqualified from acting as agent for
12 an individual who lacks capacity to make health care decisions if:
13 1. A court finds that the potential agent poses a danger to the
14 individual’s well-being, even if the court does not issue a
15 restraining order against the potential agent; or
16 2. The potential agent is an owner, operator, employee, or
17 contractor of a nursing home, or other residential care facility, in
18 which the individual resides or is receiving care, unless the owner,
19 operator, employee, or contractor is a family member of the
20 individual, the cohabitant of the individual, or a descendant of the
21 cohabitant.
22 C. A health care decision made by an agent is effective without
23 judicial approval.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 17

1 D. A power of attorney for health care shall be in a record,
2 signed by the individual creating the power, and signed by an adult
3 witness who:
4 1. Reasonably believes the act of the individual to create the
5 power of attorney is voluntary and knowing; and
6 2. Is not:
7 a. the agent appointed by the individual,
8 b. the agent’s spouse or cohabitant, or
9 c. if the individual resides or is receiving care in a
10 nursing home, or other residential care facility, the
11 owner, operator, employee, or contractor of the
12 nursing home or other residential care facility; and
13 3. Is present when the individual signs the power of attorney
14 or when the individual represents that the power of attorney
15 reflects the individual’s wishes.
16 E. A witness under subsection D of this section is considered
17 present if the witness and the individual are:
18 1. Physically present in the same location;
19 2. Using electronic means that allow for real time audio and
20 visual transmission and communication in real time to the same
21 extent as if the witness and the individual were physically present
22 in the same location; or
23 3. Able to speak to and hear each other in real time through
24 audio connection if:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 18

1 a. the identity of the individual is personally known to
2 the witness, or
3 b. the witness is able to authenticate the identity of
4 the individual by receiving accurate answers from the
5 individual that enables the authentication.
6 F. A power of attorney for health care may include a health
7 care instruction.
8 SECTION 9. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.9 of Title 63, unless there
10 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 A. An individual may create an advance health care directive
12 that addresses only mental health care for the individual. The
13 advance mental health care directive may include a health care
14 instruction, a power of attorney for health care, or both.
15 B. A health care instruction under this section may include the
16 individual’s:
17 1. General philosophy and objectives regarding mental health
18 care; and
19 2. Specific goals, preferences, and wishes regarding the
20 provision, withholding, or withdrawal of a form of mental health
21 care, including:
22 a. preferences regarding professionals, programs, and
23 facilities,
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 19

1 b. admission to a mental health facility, including
2 duration of admission,
3 c. preferences regarding medications,
4 d. refusal to accept a specific type of mental health
5 care, including a medication, and
6 e. preferences regarding crisis intervention.
7 C. A power of attorney for health care under this section may
8 appoint an agent to make decisions only for mental health care.
9 D. An individual may direct in an advance mental health care
10 directive that, if the individual is experiencing a psychiatric or
11 psychological event specified in the directive, the individual may
12 not revoke the directive or a part of the directive.
13 E. If an advance mental health care directive includes a
14 direction under subsection D of this section, the advance mental
15 health care directive shall be in a record that is separate from any
16 other advance health care directive created by the individual and
17 signed by the individual creating the advance mental health care
18 directive and at least two adult witnesses who:
19 1. Attest that to the best of their knowledge the individual:
20 a. understood the nature and consequences of the
21 direction, including its risks and benefits, and
22 b. made the direction voluntarily and without coercion or
23 undue influence;
24 2. Are not:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 20

1 a. the agent appointed by the individual,
2 b. the agent’s spouse, or cohabitant, and
3 c. if the individual resides in a nursing home, or other
4 residential care facility, the owner, operator,
5 employee, or contractor of the nursing home or other
6 residential care facility; and
7 3. Are physically present in the same location as the
8 individual.
9 SECTION 10. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.10 of Title 63, unless
11 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. If a direction in an advance mental health care directive of
13 an individual conflicts with a direction in another advance health
14 care directive of the individual, the later direction revokes the
15 earlier direction to the extent of the conflict.
16 B. An appointment of an agent to make decisions only for mental
17 health care for an individual does not revoke an earlier appointment
18 of an agent to make other health care decisions for the individual.
19 A later appointment revokes the authority of an agent under the
20 earlier appointment to make decisions about mental health care
21 unless otherwise specified in the power of attorney making the later
22 appointment.
23 C. An appointment of an agent to make health care decisions for
24 an individual other than decisions about mental health care made
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 21

1 afte r appointment of an agent authorized to make only mental health
2 care decisions does not revoke the appointment of the agent
3 authorized to make only mental health care decisions.
4 SECTION 11. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.11 of Title 63, unless
6 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 The following form may be used to create an advance health care
8 directive:
9 ADVANCE HEALTH CARE DIRECTIVE
10 HOW YOU CAN USE THIS FORM
11 You can use this form if you wish to name someone to make health
12 care decisions for you in case you cannot make decisions for
13 yourself. This is called giving the person a power of attorney for
14 health care. This person is called your agent.
15 You can also use this form to state your wishes, preferences,
16 and goals for health care, and to say if you want to be an organ
17 donor after you die.
18 YOUR NAME AND DATE OF BIRTH
19 Name:
20 Date of birth:
21 PART A: NAMING AN AGENT
22 This part lets you name someone else to make health care
23 decisions for you. You may leave any item blank.
24 1. NAMING AN AGENT
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 22

1 I want the following person to make health care decisions for me
2 if I cannot make decisions for myself:
3 Name:
4 Optional contact information (it is helpful to include
5 information such as address, phone, and email):
6 2. NAMING AN ALTERNATE AGENT
7 I want the following person to make health care decisions for me
8 if I cannot and my agent is not able or available to make them for
9 me:
10 Name:
11 Optional contact information (it is helpful to include
12 information such as address, phone, and email):
13 3. LIMITING YOUR AGENT’S AUTHORITY
14 I give my agent the power to make all health care decisions for
15 me if I cannot make those decisions for myself, except the
16 following:
17 (If you do not add a limitation here, your agent will be able to
