1 SECTION 12. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.12 of Title 63, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. A default surrogate may make a health care decision for an
5 individual who lacks capacity to make health care decisions and for
6 whom an agent, or guardian authorized to make health care decisions,
7 has not been appointed or is not reasonably available.
8 B. Unless the individual has an advance health care directive
9 that indicates otherwise, a member of the following classes, in
10 descending order of priority, who is reasonably available and not
11 disqualified under Section 14 of this act, may act as a default
12 surrogate for the individual:
13 1. An adult the individual has identified, other than in a
14 power of attorney for health care, to make a health care decision
15 for the individual if the individual cannot make the decision;
16 2. The individual’s spouse, unless:
17 a. a petition for annulment, divorce, dissolution of
18 marriage, legal separation, or termination has been
19 filed and not dismissed or withdrawn,
20 b. a decree of annulment, divorce, dissolution of
21 marriage, legal separation, or termination has been
22 issued,
23 c. the individual and the spouse have agreed in a record
24 to a legal separation, or
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 32

1 d. the spouse has abandoned the individual for more than
2 one (1) year;
3 3. The individual’s adult child or parent;
4 4. The individual’s cohabitant;
5 5. The individual’s adult sibling;
6 6. The individual’s adult grandchild or grandparent;
7 7. An adult not listed in paragraphs 1 through 6 of this
8 subsection who has assisted the individual with supported decision
9 making routinely during the preceding six (6) months;
10 8. The individual’s adult stepchild not listed in paragraphs 1
11 through 7 of this subsection whom the individual actively parented
12 during the stepchild’s minor years and with whom the individual has
13 an ongoing relationship; or
14 9. An adult not listed in paragraphs 1 through 8 of this
15 subsection who has exhibited special care and concern for the
16 individual and is familiar with the individual’s personal values.
17 C. A responsible health care professional may require an
18 individual who assumes authority to act as a default surrogate to
19 provide a declaration in a record under penalty of perjury stating
20 facts and circumstances reasonably sufficient to establish the
21 authority.
22 D. If a responsible health care professional reasonably
23 determines that an individual who assumed authority to act as a
24 default surrogate is not willing or able to comply with a duty under
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 33

1 Sect ion 17 of this act or fails to comply with the duty in a timely
2 manner, the professional may recognize the individual next in
3 priority under subsection B of this section as the default
4 surrogate.
5 E. A health care decision made by a default surrogate is
6 effective without judicial approval.
7 F. Prior to making a health care decision for an individual
8 pursuant to subsection A of this section, a responsible health care
9 professional may require a default surrogate to provide to the
10 responsible health care professional a signed copy of the following
11 statement to be entered into the patient’s medical record:
12 “I hereby certify that:
13 I have not been convicted of, pleaded guilty to, or pleaded no
14 contest to the crimes of abuse, verbal abuse, neglect, or financial
15 exploitation by a caregiver; exploitation of an elderly person or
16 disabled adult; or abuse, neglect, exploitation, or sexual abuse of
17 a child;
18 I have not been found to have committed abuse, verbal abuse, or
19 exploitation by a final investigative finding of the State
20 Department of Health or the Department of Human Services or by a
21 finding of an administrative law judge, unless it was overturned on
22 appeal; and I have not been criminally charged as a person
23 responsible for the care of a vulnerable adult with a crime
24 resulting in the death or near death of a vulnerable adult.”
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 34

1 SECTION 13. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.13 of Title 63, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. A default surrogate who assumes authority under Section 12
5 of this act shall inform a responsible health care professional if
6 two or more members of a class under subsection B of Section 12 of
7 this act have assumed authority to act as default surrogates and the
8 members do not agree on a health care decision.
9 B. A responsible health care professional shall comply with the
10 decision of a majority of the members of the class with highest
11 priority under subsection B of Section 12 of this act who have
12 communicated their views to the professional and who the
13 professional reasonably believes are acting consistently with their
14 duties under Section 17 of this act.
15 C. If a responsible health care professional is informed that
16 the members of the class who have communicated their views to the
17 professional are evenly divided concerning the health care decision,
18 the professional shall make a reasonable effort to solicit the views
19 of members of the class who are reasonably available but have not
20 yet communicated their views to the professional. The professional,
21 after the solicitation, shall comply with the decision of a majority
22 of the members who have communicated their views to the professional
23 and who the professional reasonably believes are acting consistently
24 with their duties under Section 17 of this act.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 35

1 D. If the class remains evenly divided after the effort is made
2 under subsection C of this section, the health care decision shall
3 be made as provided by other laws of this state regarding the
4 treatment of an individual who is found to lack capacity.
5 E. Nothing in this section shall be construed to supersede or
6 limit the remedies available under Section 27 of this act.
7 SECTION 14. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.14 of Title 63, unless
9 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 A. An individual for whom a health care decision would be made
11 may disqualify another individual from acting as default surrogate
12 for the first individual. The disqualification shall be in a record
13 signed by the first individual or communicated verbally or
14 nonverbally to the individual being disqualified, another
15 individual, or a responsible health care professional.
16 Disqualification under this subsection shall be effective even if
17 made by an individual who lacks capacity to make an advance
18 directive if the individual clearly communicates a desire that the
19 individual being disqualified cannot make health care decisions for
20 the individual.
21 B. An individual is disqualified from acting as a default
22 surrogate for an individual who lacks capacity to make health care
23 decisions if:
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 36

1 1. A court finds that the potential default surrogate poses a
2 danger to the individual’s well-being, even if the court does not
3 issue a restraining order against the potential surrogate;
4 2. The potential default surrogate is an owner, operator,
5 employee, or contractor of a nursing home, or other residential care
6 facility, in which the individual is residing or receiving care
7 unless the owner, operator, employee, or contractor is a family
8 member of the individual, the cohabitant of the individual, or a
9 descendant of the cohabitant; or
10 3. The potential default surrogate refuses to provide a timely
11 declaration under subsection C or F of Section 12 of this act.
12 SECTION 15. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.15 of Title 63, unless
14 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 A. An individual may revoke the appointment of an agent, the
16 designation of a default surrogate, or a health care instruction in
17 whole or in part, unless:
18 1. A court finds the individual lacks capacity to do so;
19 2. The individual is found under subsection B of Section 4 of
20 this act to lack capacity to do so, and if the individual objects to
21 the finding, the finding is confirmed under paragraph 4 of
22 subsection D of Section 5 of this act and is not revoked under
23 Section 6 of this act; or
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 37

1 3. The individual created an advance mental health care
2 directive that includes the provision under subsection D of Section
3 9 of this act, and the individual is experiencing the psychiatric or
4 psychological event specified in the directive.
5 B. Revocation under subsection A of this section may be by any
6 act of the individual that clearly indicates that the individual
7 intends to revoke the appointment, designation, or instruction,
8 including an oral statement to a health care professional.
9 C. Except as provided in Section 10 of this act, an advance
10 health care directive of an individual that conflicts with another
11 advance health care directive of the individual revokes the earlier
12 directive to the extent of the conflict.
13 D. Unless otherwise provided in an individual’s advance health
14 care directive appointing an agent, the appointment of a spouse of
15 an individual as agent for the individual is revoked if:
16 1. A petition for annulment, divorce, dissolution of marriage,
17 legal separation, or termination has been filed and not dismissed or
18 withdrawn;
19 2. A decree of annulment, divorce, dissolution of marriage,
20 legal separation, or termination has been issued;
21 3. The individual and the spouse have agreed in a record to a
22 legal separation; or
23 4. The spouse has abandoned the individual for more than one
24 (1) year.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 38

1 SECTION 16. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.16 of Title 63, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. Subject to subsection C of Section 19 of this act, an
5 advance health care directive created outside this state is valid if
6 it complies with:
7 1. The law of the state specified in the directive or, if a
8 state is not specified, the state in which the individual created
9 the directive; or
10 2. The provisions of this act.
11 B. A person may assume without inquiry that an advance health
12 care directive is genuine, valid, and still in effect, and may
13 implement and rely on it, unless the person has good cause to
14 believe the directive is invalid or has been revoked.
15 C. An advance health care directive, revocation of a directive,
16 or a signature on a directive or revocation may not be denied legal
17 effect or enforceability solely because it is in electronic form.
18 D. Evidence relating to an advance health care directive,
19 revocation of a directive, or a signature on a directive or
20 revocation may not be excluded in a proceeding solely because the
21 evidence is in electronic form.
22 E. This act shall not affect the validity of an electronic
23 record or signature that is valid under Section 15-101 et seq. of
24 Title 12A of the Oklahoma Statutes.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 39

1 F. Except as provided in subsections D and E of Section 19,
2 Section 21, subsection H of Section 22, and subsections A and D of
3 Section 28 of this act, if this act conflicts with any other law of
4 this state relating to the creation, execution, implementation, or
5 revocation of an advance health care directive, the provisions of
6 this act shall prevail.
7 SECTION 17. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.17 of Title 63, unless
9 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 A. An agent or default surrogate has a fiduciary duty to the
11 individual for whom the agent or default surrogate is acting when
12 exercising or purporting to exercise a power under Section 18 of
13 this act.
14 B. An agent or default surrogate shall make a health care
15 decision in accordance with the direction of the individual in an
16 advance health care directive and other goals, preferences, and
17 wishes of the individual to the extent known or reasonably
18 ascertainable by the agent or default surrogate.
19 C. If there is not a direction in an advance health care
20 directive and the goals, preferences, and wishes of the individual
21 regarding a health care decision are not known or reasonably
22 ascertainable by the agent or default surrogate, the agent or
23 default surrogate shall make the decision in accordance with the
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 40

1 agen t’s or default surrogate’s reasonable determination of the
2 individual’s best interest.
3 D. In determining the individual’s best interest under
4 subsection C of this section, the agent or default surrogate shall:
5 1. Give primary consideration to the individual’s
6 contemporaneous communications, including verbal and nonverbal
7 expressions;
8 2. Consider the individual’s values to the extent known or
9 reasonably ascertainable by the agent or default surrogate; and
10 3. Consider the risks and benefits of the potential health care
11 decision.
12 E. As soon as reasonably feasible, an agent or default
13 surrogate who is informed of a revocation of an advance health care
14 directive or disqualification of the agent or default surrogate
15 shall communicate the revocation or disqualification to a
16 responsible health care professional.
17 SECTION 18. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.18 of Title 63, unless
19 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 A. Except as provided in subsection C of this section, the
21 power of an agent or default surrogate commences when the individual
22 is found under subsection B of Section 4 of this act or by a court
23 to lack capacity to make a health care decision. The power shall
24 cease if the individual later is found to have capacity to make a
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 41

1 heal th care decision, or the individual objects under subsection C
2 of Section 5 of this act to the finding of lack of capacity under
3 subsection B of Section 4 of this act. Subject to subsection E of
4 Section 5 of this act, the power shall resume if:
5 1. The power ceased because the individual objected under
6 subsection C of Section 5 of this act; and
7 2. The finding of lack of capacity is confirmed under paragraph
8 4 of subsection D of Section 5 of this act, or a court finds that
9 the individual lacks capacity to make a health care decision.
10 B. An agent or default surrogate may request, receive, examine,
11 copy, and consent to the disclosure of medical and other health care
12 information about the individual if the individual would have the
13 right to request, receive, examine, copy, or consent to the
14 disclosure of the information.
15 C. A power of attorney for health care may provide that the
16 power of an agent under subsection B of this section commences on
17 appointment.
18 D. If no other person is authorized to do so, an agent or
19 default surrogate may apply for public or private health insurance
20 and benefits on behalf of the individual. An agent or default
21 surrogate who may apply for insurance and benefits does not, solely
22 by reason of the power, have a duty to apply for the insurance or
23 benefits.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 42

1 E. An agent or default surrogate may not consent to voluntary
2 admission of the individual to a facility for mental health
3 treatment unless:
4 1. Voluntary admission is specifically authorized by the
5 individual in an advance health care directive in a record; and
6 2. The admission is for no more than the maximum of the number
7 of days specified in the directive.
8 F. Except as provided in subsection G of this section, an agent
9 or default surrogate may not consent to placement of the individual
10 in a nursing home, other than for short-term rehabilitation services
11 following hospitalization, if the individual objects to the
12 placement and a reasonable alternative living arrangement is
13 feasible.
14 G. If specifically authorized by the individual in an advance
15 health care directive in a record, an agent or default surrogate may
16 consent to placement of the individual in a nursing home even if a
17 reasonable alternative living arrangement is feasible.
18 SECTION 19. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.19 of Title 63, unless
20 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. If an individual has a long-term disability requiring
22 routine treatment by mechanical ventilation and a history of using
23 the treatment without objection, an agent or default surrogate may
24 not consent to withhold or withdraw the treatment unless:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 43

1 1. The treatment is both not necessary to sustain the
2 individual’s life and not necessary to maintain the individual’s
3 health or well-being;
4 2. The individual has expressly authorized the withholding or
5 withdrawal in a health care instruction that has not been revoked;
6 or
7 3. The individual has experienced a life-threatening condition
8 that is not curable and is expected to cause the individual to die
9 within two weeks, even if treated, and the individual has not:
10 a. given a direction inconsistent with withholding or
11 withdrawal, or
12 b. communicated by verbal or nonverbal expression a
13 desire for mechanical ventilation.
14 B. An advance directive that is executed in this state shall
15 not be deemed to authorize the withholding or withdrawal of
16 artificially administered nutrition or hydration unless it
17 specifically authorizes the withholding or withdrawal of
18 artificially administered nutrition or hydration in the declarant’s
19 own words or by a separate section, separate paragraph, or other
20 separate subdivision that deals only with nutrition or hydration and
21 which section, paragraph, or other subdivision is separately
22 initialed, separately signed, or otherwise separately marked by the
23 declarant.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 44

1 C. Execution of an advance directive by an individual that
2 provides for the provision, withholding, or withdrawal of life-
3 sustaining treatment for the individual or for the appointment of
4 another to give directions to provide, withhold, or withdraw life-
5 sustaining treatment, executed in another state in compliance with
6 the laws of that state or of this state, shall be valid for purposes
7 of the this act to the extent the advance directive does not exceed
8 authorizations allowed under the laws of this state. No such
9 advance directive shall be deemed to authorize the withholding or
10 withdrawal of artificially administered nutrition or hydration
11 unless it specifically authorizes such withholding or withdrawal,
12 and the advance directive either:
13 1. Was executed by a person who was not a resident of this
14 state at the time of execution; or
15 2. Specifically authorizes the withholding or withdrawal of
16 artificially administered nutrition or hydration in the declarant’s
17 own words or by a separate section, separate paragraph, or other
18 separate subdivision that deals only with nutrition or hydration,
19 and such section, paragraph, or other subdivision is separately
20 initialed, separately signed, or otherwise separately marked by the
21 person executing the advance directive.
22 D. Decisions by a default surrogate or agent to consent to
23 withholding or withdrawal of nutrition or hydration are subject to
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 45

1 the provisions of the Hydration and Nutrition for Incompetent
2 Patients Act.
3 E. A default surrogate may not make a health care decision if,
4 under other laws of this state, the decision:
5 1. May not be made by a guardian; or
6 2. May be made by a guardian only if the court appointing the
7 guardian specifically authorizes the guardian to make the decision.
8 SECTION 20. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.20 of Title 63, unless
10 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 A. An individual in a power of attorney for health care may
12 appoint multiple individuals as coagents. Unless the power of
13 attorney provides otherwise, each coagent may exercise independent
14 authority.
15 B. An individual in a power of attorney for health care may
16 appoint one or more individuals to act as alternate agents if a
17 predecessor agent resigns, dies, becomes disqualified, is not
18 reasonably available, or otherwise is unwilling or unable to act as
19 agent.
20 C. Unless the power of attorney provides otherwise, an
21 alternate agent has the same authority as the original agent:
22 1. At any time the original agent is not reasonably available
23 or is otherwise unwilling or unable to act, for the duration of the
24 unavailability, unwillingness, or inability to act; or
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 46

1 2. If the original agent and all other predecessor agents have
2 resigned or died or are disqualified from acting as agent.
3 SECTION 21. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
4 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.21 of Title 63, unless
5 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
6 No person shall be authorized as a default surrogate to make
7 health care decisions for a patient if that person:
8 1. Has been convicted of, pled guilty to, or pled no contest to
9 any violation of Section 843.1, 843.2, 843.4, or 843.5 of Title 21
10 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
11 2. Has been found to have committed abuse, verbal abuse, or
12 exploitation, as defined in Section 10-103 of Title 43A of the
13 Oklahoma Statutes, by a final State Department of Health or
14 Department of Human Services investigative finding, or by an
15 administrative law judge finding, unless that finding has been
16 overturned through judicial review; or
17 3. Has been criminally charged as described in subsection B of
18 Section 10-110.1 of Title 43A of the Oklahoma Statutes, unless the
19 person has been acquitted or those charges have been finally
20 dismissed.
21 SECTION 22. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.22 of Title 63, unless
23 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 47

1 A. A responsible health care professional who is aware that an
2 individual has been found to lack capacity to make a decision shall
3 make a reasonable effort to determine if the individual has a
4 surrogate.
5 B. If possible before implementing a health care decision made
6 by a surrogate, a responsible health care professional, as soon as
7 reasonably feasible, shall communicate to the individual the
8 decision made and the identity of the surrogate.
9 C. A responsible health care professional who makes or is
10 informed of a finding that an individual lacks capacity to make a
11 health care decision or no longer lacks capacity, or that other
12 circumstances exist that affect a health care instruction or the
13 authority of a surrogate, as soon as reasonably feasible, shall:
14 1. Document the finding or circumstance in the individual’s
15 medical record; and
16 2. If possible, communicate to the individual and the
17 individual’s surrogate the finding or circumstance and that the
18 individual may object under subsection C of Section 5 of this act to
19 the finding under subsection B of Section 4 of this act.
20 D. A responsible health care professional who is informed that
21 an individual has created or revoked an advance health care
22 directive, or that a surrogate for an individual has been appointed,
23 designated, or disqualified, shall:
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 48

1 1. Document the information as soon as reasonably feasible in
2 the individual’s medical record; and
3 2. If evidence of the directive, revocation, appointment,
4 designation, or disqualification is in a record, request a copy and,
5 upon receipt, cause the copy to be included in the individual’s
6 medical record.
7 E. Except as provided in subsections F and G of this section, a
8 health care professional or health care institution providing health
9 care to an individual shall comply with:
10 1. A health care instruction given by the individual regarding
11 the individual’s health care;
12 2. A reasonable interpretation by the individual’s surrogate of
13 an instruction given by the individual; and
14 3. A health care decision for the individual made by the
15 individual’s surrogate in accordance with Sections 17 and 18 of this
16 act to the same extent as if the decision had been made by the
17 individual at a time when the individual had capacity.
18 F. A health care professional or a health care institution may
19 refuse to provide health care consistent with a health care
20 instruction or health care decision if:
21 1. The instruction or decision is contrary to a policy of the
22 health care institution providing care to the individual that is
23 based expressly on reasons of conscience, and the policy was timely
24 communicated to the individual or to the individual’s surrogate;
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 49

1 2. The care would require health care that is not available to
2 the professional or institution; or
3 3. Compliance with the instruction or decision would:
4 a. require the professional to provide care that is
5 contrary to the professional’s religious belief or
6 moral conviction if other law permits the professional
7 to refuse to provide care for that reason,
8 b. require the professional or institution to provide
9 care that is contrary to generally accepted health
10 care standards applicable to the professional or
11 institution, or
12 c. violate a court order or other law.
13 G. A health care professional or health care institution that
14 refuses to provide care under subsection F of this section shall:
15 1. As soon as reasonably feasible, inform the individual, if
16 possible, and the individual’s surrogate of the refusal;
17 2. Immediately make a reasonable effort to transfer the
18 individual to another health care professional or health care
19 institution that is willing to comply with the instruction or
20 decision; and
21 3. Either:
22 a. if care is refused under paragraph 1 or 2 of
23 subsection F of this section, provide life-sustaining
24 care and care needed to keep or make the individual
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 50

1 comfortable, consistent with accepted medical
2 standards to the extent feasible, until a transfer is
3 made, or
4 b. if care is refused under paragraph 3 of subsection F
5 of this section, provide life-sustaining care and care
6 needed to keep or make the individual comfortable,
7 consistent with accepted medical standards, until a
8 transfer is made.
9 H. As used in this section, “generally accepted health care
10 standards” and “accepted medical standards” shall not be interpreted
11 to supersede, or to authorize any violation of, the
12 Nondiscrimination in Treatment Act.
13 SECTION 23. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.23 of Title 63, unless
15 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 A. A guardian may refuse to comply with or revoke the
17 individual’s advance health care directive only if the court
18 appointing the guardian expressly orders the noncompliance or
19 revocation.
20 B. Unless a court orders otherwise, a health care decision made
21 by an agent appointed by an individual subject to guardianship
22 prevails over a decision of the guardian appointed for the
23 individual.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 51

1 SECTION 24. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.24 of Title 63, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. A health care professional or health care institution acting
5 in good faith shall not be subject to civil or criminal liability or
6 to discipline for unprofessional conduct for:
7 1. Complying with a health care decision made for an individual
8 by another person if compliance is based on a reasonable belief that
9 the person has authority to make the decision, including a decision
10 to withhold or withdraw health care;
11 2. Refusing to comply with a health care decision made for an
12 individual by another person if the refusal is based on a reasonable
13 belief that the person lacked authority or capacity to make the
14 decision;
15 3. Complying with an advance health care directive based on a
16 reasonable belief that the directive is valid;
17 4. Refusing to comply with an advance health care directive
18 based on a reasonable belief that the directive is not valid,
19 including a reasonable belief that the directive was not made by the
20 individual or, after its creation, was substantively altered by a
21 person other than the individual who created it;
22 5. Determining that an individual who otherwise might be
23 authorized to act as an agent or default surrogate is not reasonably
24 available; or
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 52

1 6. Complying with an individual’s direction under subsection D
2 of Section 9 of this act.
3 B. An agent, default surrogate, or individual with a reasonable
4 belief that the individual is an agent or a default surrogate shall
5 not be subject to civil or criminal liability or to discipline for
6 unprofessional conduct for a health care decision made in a good
7 faith effort to comply with Section 17 of this act.
8 SECTION 25. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
9 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.25 of Title 63, unless
10 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
11 A. A person shall not:
12 1. Intentionally falsify, in whole or in part, an advance
13 health care directive;
14 2. For the purpose of frustrating the intent of the individual
15 who created an advance health care directive or with knowledge that
16 doing so is likely to frustrate the intent:
17 a. intentionally conceal, deface, obliterate, or delete
18 the directive or a revocation of the directive without
19 consent of the individual who created or revoked the
20 directive, or
21 b. intentionally withhold knowledge of the existence or
22 revocation of the directive from a responsible health
23 care professional or health care institution providing
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 53

1 health care to the individual who created or revoked
2 the directive;
3 3. Coerce or fraudulently induce an individual to create,
4 revoke, or refrain from creating or revoking an advance health care
5 directive or a part of a directive; or
6 4. Require or prohibit the creation or revocation of an advance
7 health care directive as a condition for providing health care.
8 B. An individual who is the subject of conduct prohibited under
9 subsection A of this section, or the individual’s estate, shall have
10 a cause of action against a person who violates subsection A of this
11 section for statutory damages of Twenty-five Thousand Dollars
12 ($25,000.00) or actual damages resulting from the violation,
13 whichever is greater.
14 C. Subject to subsection D of this section, an individual who
15 makes a health care instruction, or the individual’s estate, shall
16 have a cause of action against a health care professional or health
17 care institution that intentionally violates Section 22 of this act
18 for statutory damages of Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) or
19 actual damages resulting from the violation, whichever is greater.
20 D. A health care professional who is an emergency medical
21 responder shall not be liable under subsection C of this section for
22 a violation of subsection E of Section 22 of this act if:
23 1. The violation occurs in the course of providing care to an
24 individual experiencing a health condition for which the
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 54

1 prof essional reasonably believes the care was appropriate to avoid
2 imminent loss of life or serious harm to the individual;
3 2. The failure to comply is consistent with accepted standards
4 of the profession of the professional; and
5 3. The provision of care does not begin in a health care
6 institution in which the individual resides or was receiving care.
7 E. In an action under this section, a prevailing plaintiff may
8 recover reasonable attorney fees, court costs, and other reasonable
9 litigation expenses.
10 F. A cause of action or remedy under this section shall be in
11 addition to any cause of action or remedy under any other law.
12 SECTION 26. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.26 of Title 63, unless
14 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 A. A physical or electronic copy of an advance health care
16 directive, revocation of an advance health care directive, or
17 appointment, designation, or disqualification of a surrogate has the
18 same effect as the original.
19 B. An individual may create a certified physical copy of an
20 advance health care directive or revocation of an advance health
21 care directive that is in electronic form by affirming under penalty
22 of perjury that the physical copy is a complete and accurate copy of
23 the directive or revocation.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 55

1 SECTION 27. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.27 of Title 63, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. On petition of an individual, the individual’s surrogate, a
5 health care professional or health care institution providing health
6 care to the individual, or a person interested in the welfare of the
7 individual, the court may:
8 1. Enjoin implementation of a health care decision made by an
9 agent or default surrogate on behalf of the individual, on a finding
10 that the decision is inconsistent with Section 17 or 18 of this act;
11 2. Enjoin an agent from making a health care decision for the
12 individual, on a finding that the individual’s appointment of the
13 agent has been revoked or the agent:
14 a. is disqualified under subsection B of Section 8 or
15 under Section 21 of this act,
16 b. is unwilling or unable to comply with Section 17 of
17 this act, or
18 c. poses a danger to the individual’s well-being;
19 3. Enjoin another individual from acting as a default
20 surrogate, on a finding that the other individual acting as a
21 default surrogate did not comply with Section 12 of this act or the
22 other individual:
23 a. is disqualified under Section 14 or 21 of this act,
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 56

1 b. is unwilling or unable to comply with Section 17 of
2 this act, or
3 c. poses a danger to the first individual’s well-being,
4 and authorize another member of the classes identified in subsection
5 B of Section 12 of this act who is able and willing to comply with
6 the provisions of this act to serve as the individual’s default
7 surrogate in place of the enjoined surrogate; or
8 4. Order implementation of a health care decision made:
9 a. by and for the individual, or
10 b. by an agent or default surrogate who is acting in
11 compliance with the powers and duties of the agent or
12 default surrogate.
13 B. In this act, advocacy for the provision, withholding, or
14 withdrawal of health care or mental health care to or from an
15 individual is not itself evidence that an agent or default
16 surrogate, or a potential agent or default surrogate, poses a danger
17 to the individual’s well-being.
18 C. A proceeding under this section shall be governed by
19 Sections 2-101 et seq. and 3-101 et seq. of Title 30 of the Oklahoma
20 Statutes.
21 SECTION 28. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3100.28 of Title 63, unless
23 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1687 Page 57

1 A. This act shall not authorize mercy killing, assisted
2 suicide, or euthanasia, and is subject to the provisions of the
3 Assisted Suicide Prevention Act.
4 B. This act shall not affect other laws of this state governing
5 treatment for mental illness of an individual involuntarily
6 committed to a mental health care institution under Section 5-410 et
7 seq. of Title 43A of the Oklahoma Statutes.
8 C. Death of an individual caused by withholding or withdrawing
9 health care in accordance with this act shall not constitute a
10 suicide or homicide or legally impair or invalidate a policy of
11 insurance or an annuity providing a death benefit, notwithstanding
12 any term of the policy or annuity.
13 D. This act shall not create a presumption concerning the
14 intention of an individual who has not created an advance health
15 care directive, except as provided in the Hydration and Nutrition
16 for Incompetent Patients Act.
17 E. An advance health care directive created before, on, or
18 after the effective date of this act shall be interpreted in
19 accordance with the laws of this state, excluding the state’s choice
20 of law rules, at the time the directive is implemented.
